@database psselect.guide

@width 72

@node main "psselect.guide"

PSUtils Release 1 Patchlevel 16

NAME

psselect - select pages from a PostScript file


SYNOPSIS

@{b}psselect@{ub} [@{b}-q@{ub}] [@{b}-e@{ub}] [@{b}-o@{ub}] [@{b}-r@{ub}] [@{b}-p@{ub}@{i}pages@{ui}][,@{i}pages@{ui}] [@{i}infile@{ui} [@{i}outfile@{ui}] ]

@{i}`Online help' : @{ui}@{b} psselect -?@{ub}

DESCRIPTION

@{i}Psselect@{ui} selects pages from a PostScript document, creating a
new PostScript file. The input PostScript file should follow the Adobe
Document Structuring Conventions.

The @{b}-e@{ub} option selects all of the even pages; it may be used in
conjunction with the other page selection options to select the even pages
from a range of pages.

The @{b}-o@{ub} option selects all of the odd pages; it may be used in
conjunction with the other page selection options.

The @{b}-p@{ub}@{i}pages@{ui} option specifies the pages which are to be selected.

@{i}Pages@{ui} is a comma separated list of page ranges, each of which may
be a page number, or a page range of the form @{i}first@{ui}@{b}-@{ub}@{i}last@{ui}.  If @{i}first@{ui}
is omitted, the first page is assumed, and if @{i}last@{ui} is omitted, the
last page is assumed.

The prefix character `@{b}_@{ub}' indicates that the page number is relative
to the end of the document, counting backwards.

The @{b}-r@{ub} option causes @{i}psselect@{ui} to output the selected pages
in reverse order.

@{i}Psselect@{ui} normally prints the page numbers of the pages rearranged;
the @{b}-q@{ub} option suppresses this.

If any of the @{b}-r@{ub}, @{b}-e@{ub}, or @{b}-o@{ub} options are specified,
the page range must be given with the @{b}-p@{ub} option. This is for
backwards compatibility with previous versions.


NOTES

The page number given to @{i}psselect@{ui} is the number of the page counting
from the start or end of the file, starting at one. The actual page number
in the document may be different.


AUTHOR

Angus Duggan


